==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mullet
<hw>Mul"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>molet</ets>,
<ets>mulet</ets>, F. <ets>mulet</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mullus</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous fishes of the
genus Mugil; -- called also <altname>gray mullets</altname>. They are
found on the coasts of both continents, and are highly esteemed as food.
Among the most valuable species are <styp><spn>Mugil capito</spn></styp>
of Europe, and <styp><spn>Mugil cephalus</spn></styp> which occurs both
on the European and American coasts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of the genus
<gen>Mullus</gen>, or family <fam>Mullidae</fam>; called also
<altname>red mullet</altname>, and <altname>surmullet</altname>, esp.
the plain surmullet (<spn>Mullus barbatus</spn>), and the striped
surmullet (<spn>Mullus surmulletus</spn>) of Southern Europe. The former
is the mullet of the Romans. It is noted for the brilliancy of its
colors. See <er>Surmullet</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>French mullet</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Ladyfish</er>
<sd>(a)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mullet
<hw>Mul"let</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>molette</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A star, usually five pointed and pierced; -- when
used as a difference it indicates the third son.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mullet
<hw>Mul"let</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>molet</ets> a sort of
pinchers.]</ety> <def>Small pinchers for curling the hair.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moolley</ent>⟦br⟧
